        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We will use Band 6 in the continuum mode to obtain full polarization.
We choose Band 6 because the primary beam of the ALMA 12m antennas is well 
matched with the source size. We will use configuration C34-4 to achieve 
an angular resolution of 0.5", matching the core structure revealed in the SMA 
continuum images. This configuration is sensitive to structures of 8" 
in Band 6, which is well matched with the maximum size of our target. 
Moreover, the emission from B335 will be contained within 1/3 of the primary beam. 

We propose to carry out polarization observations of the dust continuum emission around 220\,GHz in Band 6, 
so that the polarized dust continuum emission does not exceed half of the primary beam (compromise optically thin / resolution). 
observations imply that the core is a star of mass $\sim$0.5$\msol$ (Zhou et al. 1990), 
and it was proposed it harbors a circumstellar disk $\sim$100--200 AU in diameter (Harvey et al. 2003a). 
We need to trace the magnetic fields distribution down to the scale of the putative disk to test magnetic braking efficiency.
We will therefore use the {\bf{C34-4 configuration}} which provides a synthesized beam of $\sim$0.5$\arcsec$ in Band 6, eg FWHM$\sim$75 AU at the distance of B335. 

Using a spectral index of 1.5 derived from 1.3 and 0.8 mm observations, we expect a Stokes I flux of about 2 mJy/beam in the ALMA 0.5$\arcsec$ synthesized beam at 220 GHz.
Assuming a conservative polarization percentage of 2\% of the peak, the polarized flux is expected to be ~80 microJy/beam in our proposed observations.
We therefore need a rms sensitivity 15 microJy/beam to obtain a signal-to-noise ratio $\sim$5 (S/N$\sim$5 corresponds to an error on the magnetic field lines vectors of $\sim$45$^{\circ}$).
Therefore we request {\bf{a total of $\sim$XXXh observing time taking into account the overheads in the polarization observing mode in Band 6}}. Note that {\bf{only ALMA can do that}}. 

 PI and co-Is have extensive experience dealing with 
polarization calibration of the SMA data. We are willing to assist in ALMA 
data calibration is needed.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
